  {
    title: 'We Just Wanna Go Home',
    lyrics: `[Verse 1]
Buried City spawn—sand lot, bus sign gone.
Wind over dunes, rusted billboard yawn.
Dead lamps tick above the metro mouth.
Half-buried stairs. Ticket hall, ghosted out.
Sun-bleached map—arrows rubbed to stone.
Rail hum below. We move. It's on.

[Pre-Chorus]
Buried City's a trap—so fucking dangerous.
Every corner's a crosshair—yeah, it aims at us.

[Chorus]
GUYS! WE JUST WANNA GO HOME!
Hands low—no crown, no throne.
GUYS! WE JUST WANNA GO HOME!
We're just lookin' for some lemon.

[Verse 2]
Loading dock lamps—shadows bloom.
Three raiders posted, guns assume.
Freeze—let the chrome hang low.
One deep breath—then the plea goes—

[Chorus]
GUYS! WE JUST WANNA GO HOME!
No beef tonight—let it go.
GUYS! WE JUST WANNA GO HOME!
We're just lookin' for some lemon.

[Bridge]
Same scars, same dust in our hands,
Same god of rust, same dead fans.
If there's mercy in this stone,
One train—take us home.

[Break]
Brake. Hiss.
Heads nod. No miss.

[Final Chorus]
GUYS! WE JUST WANNA GO HOME! (let us go)
Keep your rounds, keep your zone. (we don't want it)
GUYS! WE JUST WANNA GO HOME! (let us go)
Just lookin' for some lemon—then we're gone.

[Outro]
Heat to hum. Three stops.
Lamp light. Heart drops.
Home.`,
  },
  {
    title: 'Good At The End',
    lyrics: `[Verse 1]
She greeted me with: "Friendly!", sounded sweet.
I turned—she attacked; the trap was complete.
I yelled, "WHY?!" as the muzzle-flash threw me off track.
She fired; I fired—shot for shot, no looking back.
When it went quiet, she lay on the ground.
She said, "I used to be nice," in a broken sound.
"Got betrayed too many times," her voice shaking.
I said: "You're better than this," healed her, heart waking.

[Bridge / Pre-Chorus]
I said: I get it—people can be horrible, it's true.
They break you for their profit, then say it's on you.
But being horrible back don't make the poison leave.
It just turns you into them, and you start to rot and grieve.
Don't do it for them, do it for yourself.
So you don't become someone else.
She looked away like that hit harder than the fight.
She rose up on her feet, new resolve in her sight.

[Chorus]
When you fall, fall forward—don't fold.
Get back up steady, brave, not cold.
Don't let the hurt rewrite your name.
Don't let the worst decide your aim.
Take the hit, then stand up again.
Resilient to the end, again and again.

[Verse 2]
A Shredder hit the hall, metal loud.
We slid through cover, in the shroud.
I pulled its focus wide; she moved on my cue.
We didn't break or scatter; locked in, me and you.
She said, I ran alone… thought that's how you survive.
I said, Alone makes you smaller—harder to stay alive.
She breathed out slow—like peace could finally fill.
Not standing by myself… makes everything easier still.

[Bridge 2]
A Shredder came in close—no room to run.
She took the hit, went down, and whispered, I'm done.
No saving me, she said, but I found peace again.
And that's already good… before the end.

[Final Chorus]
When you fall, fall forward—don't fold.
Get back up steady, brave, not cold.
Don't let the hurt rewrite your name.
Don't let the worst decide your aim.
Take the hit, then stand up again.
Resilient to the end, again and again.`,
  },
